{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \D4, fourth-best from your longest suit — nothing else is safer against the heart slam.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Partner's 4\D splinter drove you to 6\H — twelve tricks. Count: five trumps, the black-suit tops, the diamond pair, a club ruff… eleven, and the twelfth is hiding. Your spades are 8-7-6-2 facing A-K-3: the suit looks dead. But watch what a TRUMP can do late in a hand: when you have squeezed every other card out of the defenders' hands, your smallest spade may find itself promoted to royalty. Keep every trump; they are your squeeze cards.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Win the diamond, draw trumps, cash the black tops, ruff dummy's clubs good — East's king and West's queen of clubs both fall in the wash — and then play your LAST trump. East is down to his final guards: he must keep a diamond winner, so the spade JACK — the card protecting his ten-nine — flutters away. And now the deal's quiet punchline: your EIGHT of spades, a spot card from a dead suit, wins trick thirteen. Slam made.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The trump squeeze: the same watching game as the last two boards, but the squeeze card was a trump, and the promoted winner was an eight. Notice you never guessed anything all day on this shelf — no finesse, no fifty-fifty. You counted, you conceded on your own terms, you ran your winners, and the defenders' hands did the rest. That is squeeze play: pressure, patience, and eyes open at the end.}
