{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \S4, fourth-best from your longest suit — the routine start against 6NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] A 25-point 3NT opening, raised to six. Count: four spades once the king-jack unblock, three top hearts, two diamonds, two clubs after the ace is dislodged — eleven. The twelfth is already in your hand: the FOUR of hearts. East dealt himself five hearts to your ace-king-queen-four, and if he could keep four of them the four would never grow up — but dummy's modest ten of diamonds has a claim on his attention too. One defender, two suits: the simple squeeze in its purest geometry.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] The spade four rides to your JACK — a small gift. Cash a top diamond, then rectify: lead the club QUEEN and let West's ace take it. Win the diamond return, unblock your clubs, and run the spades, overtaking the king with dummy's ace: on the ten and queen East pitches heart after heart, for his queen-jack of diamonds must stand guard against dummy's ten. From five hearts he is down to the bare jack. Dummy's heart ten to your king collects it — and now the FOUR of hearts wins trick twelve, the ace thirteen. Twelve tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] From J-9-8-3-2, East needed four hearts to outlast your holding — and dummy's diamond ten made keeping four impossible. That is all a simple squeeze is: a defender dealt one card too few for two jobs, and a declarer who ran his winners and watched. Note that the machine that first played this deal went one down — it never saw that the smallest heart at the table could become the slam. Count the defender's jobs, not just his honors.}
