[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \DA — you doubled the artificial 3\D to ask for a diamond lead, and the lead turned out to be yours: cash the ace of your own suit.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Smolen landed the heart slam in your hand, and West's double of 3\D has marked the diamond ace on your left before a card is played. Count: five trump tricks, two spades, the diamond king-queen, two top clubs — eleven, once West cashes the ace he so helpfully advertised. The twelfth must be your fifth club — and here is the astonishment of the board: East holds Q-T-9-7-5-4 of clubs, SIX of them, one more than you. It will not help him. He also owns the spade queen-jack over dummy's ten, and the trumps are about to make him choose, four times over.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West cashes the diamond ace and continues; win dummy's king, unblocking your jack. Draw trumps — West has four, so it takes every honor you own — and along the way cash the diamond queen, pitching dummy's small club: the spade ten must keep its escort. Across those middle tricks East feeds club after club to the table, four in all, clinging to his spade guard. Now reap: spade ace and king, then the club jack — covered, king — the ace felling his ten, and the SIX of clubs, fifth round of a suit East owned six of, wins trick twelve. The last club rides home under dummy's remaining trump. Slam made.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Six cards in a suit, and East still could not guard it — that is what a squeeze does to arithmetic. His real anchor was the spade queen-jack; every trump you led cost him a club, and only counting them told you the six had grown up. Two notes for the notebook: a lead-directing double is a gift that keeps giving — it placed the missing ace before trick one — and dummy's small club went away EARLY, on the diamond queen, so the spade ten stayed alive as the second threat. Feed dead wood to your winners; keep the menaces.}
