{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \SJ, top of your J-T — the safe, standard start against 6NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Stayman found no fit and power alone put you in 6NT. Count: three spades with the king-queen unblocked, the heart finesse and the ace, three diamonds, three clubs — eleven. Now look hard for the twelfth, because it is small: dummy's fourth spade is the SEVEN; your fourth club is the SEVEN. Two sevens, two threats — and East was dealt four cards in each black suit, responsible for both. Squeezes are not always about kings and queens; when the count is right, even the sevens report for duty.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Take the spade queen, then two rounds of clubs ending in your king — East's ten already falling — and back to spades: king, then the heart finesse of the jack, then the ace as your king-queen unblock completes. Rectify on your own terms: lead the heart QUEEN into West's king, while dummy's ace still commands the third round. Win his return, unblock the diamonds, and cash the third one at trick eleven — the squeeze card. East holds the spade nine and the club jack-eight: three cards, two jobs. A club leaves; your ace collects his jack; and the SEVEN of clubs wins trick thirteen. Had the spade nine gone instead, dummy's spade SEVEN would score the same trick. Twelve either way.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The smallest squeeze on the shelf: menaces of seven and seven, guards of nine and jack-eight. Nothing here looked like a slam ending — just four quiet cards arranged so East could not hold them all. The two habits that carried it: the heart queen was FED to the king on your schedule, not West's, and the last diamond waited until every black-suit winner had been counted home. West ends the hand clutching a master diamond that nobody will ever lead. When the count is right, size means nothing.}
